<br>
Now she had it again.  And it served her.  She used it to help tune out her Sire’s constant mumbling and ranting.  She was fairly sure that it was better than the previous week’s silence.  She was very much trying to look at it as a step forward, progress, healing.  But it was FRELLIN annoying.  Especially considering he spoke twice as many languages as she did, and could read several that no one spoke anymore, but he apparently found it amusing to rant in, in his own interpretation.  She’d had Emily pick her up new earphones that were nice and comfy for long wear.<br>
<br>
Right now she was perversely enjoying Johnny Cash’s version of “Hurt”.  The night before some 14-year-old wannabe Goth twit, not even old enough to understand Nine Inch Nails was before their time, had been ranting at the coffee house about the injustice of “some icky old Country Western geezer dishonoring Trent Reznor’s vision”.   Luckily the young tasted pretty good when seasoned with frustration and righteous indignation, and she’d had fun draining the idiot to submission and then sitting them down on a lecture on American cultural heritage.  The little twit had sat quietly and listened about how Cash was an original rebel, a tarnished knight who championed music without caving to stereotypes.  She was pretty sure that the little git would not be disrespecting the original Man In Black again.  It had taken the edge off her frustration and indignation too… well maybe a little bit.  But she always had liked educating people… maybe she should have gone into teaching instead of supernatural studies.  She missed her self-defense classes.  Teaching them had always involved just as much reprogramming of the idiot men who showed up thinking to pick up on women, as teaching those silly girls to stand up for themselves and walk with a purpose.  Which reminded her, she needed to sit down with Emily and make sure that one could take care of herself as well, or at least knew which end of a tazer was which.<br>
<br>
So she scooted around the house trying to feel busy.  She arranged her books and research in the den.  She reset the timers for the house lights.    Still to do: checking on the folks back at the Big House, and reporting into Grandma that there had been no real change.  Bike?  SUV?  Bike?  SUV?  The bike, she decided.  The SUV reminded her too much of Ash right now, bells, whistles, tinted armored glass.  Frell, but Hart missed the AssHole, who was going to make her laugh and buy her huge overpowered presents she didn’t need?<br>
  <br>
The cd ended and she listened aimlessly to the soft spinning whir as it wound down.  Hart went for her gloves and helmet.  Out of the corner of her eye she saw Arman sitting like a woebegone child at the bottom of the stair.  “Cher?  Ah ya goin out Cher?  Mwen malad.  Mo la… do-do. Dey is beaucoup crasseux, but it don matta, they ah still mine, and I’m fixin to get better, sure I am.”<br>
<br>
“Ki sa se bon.  I miss yat too.”  She hauled him to his feet.  SUV, she wanted him buckled into a seat.  When you move, you always misplace something that you really feel you need.  Something you have to learn to live without.  She put the walkman on the shelf next to her helmet.  You learn.<br>
